    "back_translated_text": "**Theorem.** For integers \\(a\\) and \\(b\\), if \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) are odd, then \\(a+b\\) is even.\n\n*Proof.* Since \\(a\\) is odd and \\(b\\) is odd, there exist integers \\(k\\) and \\(j\\) such that \\(a = 2k + 1\\) and \\(b = 2j + 1\\). The proof then rewrites\n\\[\na+b = (2k+1) + (2j+1).\n\\]\nIt follows that\n\\[\na+b = 2k + 2j + 2,\n\\]\nbecause\n\\[\n(2k+1) + (2j+1) = 2k + 2j + 2.\n\\]\nThen\n\\[\na+b = 2(k+j+1),\n\\]\nbecause\n\\[\n2k + 2j + 2 = 2(k+j+1).\n\\]\nTherefore \\(a+b\\) is even, and \\(k+j+1\\) is a witness for this. □",
    "original_proof": "Theorem: The sum of two odd integers is even.\n\nProof:\n1. Let a and b be two odd integers.\n2. By definition of odd integers, there exist integers k and j such that a = 2k + 1 and b = 2j + 1.\n3. Therefore, their sum is a + b = (2k + 1) + (2j + 1).\n4. By rearranging the terms, we get a + b = 2k + 2j + 2 = 2(k + j + 1).\n5. Since k + j + 1 is an integer, we conclude that a + b is even.\n",
